ce:section.ce:para:
In the performed full factorial experimental designs the significance of the main effects and the variable interactions were initially evaluated using Higher Orders Interactions Effects (HOIE) as comparison. As centre samples are used a curvature checking of the response is done by the evaluation of the significance of the curvature trough a curvature test of the main effects and the variable interactions designated as ‘Center’ test. The assessment of the significance was also done by the analysis of variance (ANOVA) through F-ratio and respective p value. The value of multiple linear regression coefficients (R

                              Multiple
                           ) of the response variables was also analysed.

Preliminary evaluations of the sensor were done with CDs obtained from a mass of CA (m

                           CA
                        ) of 1g, a volume of EDA (V

                           EDA
                        ) of 500μL diluted in 15mL of water and exposed to a microwave radiation of 700W during a microwave time (t

                           mic
                        ) of 5min. The EEM of the CDs is shown in Fig. 1
                        . The analysis of this EEM shows a main band with an excitation wavelength of 360nm and a secondary one with an excitation wavelength of 250nm and both with an emission wavelength of 460nm.

A deeper assessment of the quenching effect by the NO and ONOO− at the three pHs with different synthesis conditions (supplementary information) allowed to established rigorously the more adequate synthesis conditions in order to achieve higher quenching of NO at pH 4 and of ONOO− at pH 7 and 10. At the chosen optimum conditions (Table 1
                        ), the obtained CDs respond linearly to the concentration of NO and ONOO−. Fig. 3
                         shows typical CDs fluorescence quenching profiles.
